<paragraph blockId="4.[525,1063,421,448]" box="[525,1063,421,448]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<heading box="[525,1063,421,448]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Order 
<taxonomicName authority="Manconi &amp; Pronzato, 2002" authorityName="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" authorityYear="2002" box="[601,1063,421,448]" class="Demospongiae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Spongillida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">
Spongillida 
<bibRefCitation author="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" box="[743,1063,421,448]" firstAuthor="Manconi" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="921 - 1019" refId="ref8380" refString="Manconi R. &amp; Pronzato R. 2002. Spongillina n. subord. Lubomirskiidae, Malawispongiidae n. fam., Metaniidae, Metschnikowiidae, Palaeospongillidae, Potamolepidae, Spongillidae. In: Hooper J. N. A. &amp; van Soest R. W. M. (eds) Systema Porifera. A guide to the classification of sponges, Vol. 1: 921 - 1019. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publisher, New York. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 97" type="journal article" year="2002">Manconi &amp; Pronzato, 2002</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,487,724]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
We formally accept the new taxonomic status (rank elevation) of the previous suborder 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" authorityYear="2002" box="[1230,1365,487,513]" class="Demospongiae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Spongillida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="subOrder" subOrder="Spongillina">Spongillina</taxonomicName>
as the new order 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" authorityYear="2002" box="[353,492,522,548]" class="Demospongiae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Spongillida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Spongillida</taxonomicName>
. The definition and diagnosis (emended after 
<bibRefCitation author="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" firstAuthor="Manconi" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="921 - 1019" refId="ref8380" refString="Manconi R. &amp; Pronzato R. 2002. Spongillina n. subord. Lubomirskiidae, Malawispongiidae n. fam., Metaniidae, Metschnikowiidae, Palaeospongillidae, Potamolepidae, Spongillidae. In: Hooper J. N. A. &amp; van Soest R. W. M. (eds) Systema Porifera. A guide to the classification of sponges, Vol. 1: 921 - 1019. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publisher, New York. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 97" type="journal article" year="2002">Manconi &amp; Pronzato 2002: 921– 922</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" box="[294,674,557,584]" firstAuthor="Manconi" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="341 - 366" refId="ref8603" refString="Manconi R. &amp; Pronzato R. 2011. Suborder Spongillina (freshwater sponges). In: Pansini M., Manconi R. &amp; Pronzato R. (eds) Porifera I. Calcarea, Demospongiae (partim), Hexactinellida, Homoscleromorpha. Fauna d'Italia, vol. 46: 341 - 366. Calderini, Bologna." type="journal article" year="2011">Manconi &amp; Pronzato 2011: 348</bibRefCitation>
) are here confirmed in part; we simply erase “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1928" box="[1232,1398,557,583]" class="Demospongiae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Haplosclerida</taxonomicName>
with” from the beginning of the diagnosis; we add strongyles among megascleres, and we anticipate the presence of the earliest fossil of the taxon at the Upper Carboniferous. We also add a final sentence which states: “The order 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" authorityYear="2002" box="[488,623,663,689]" class="Demospongiae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Spongillida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Spongillida</taxonomicName>
is cosmopolitan in freshwater and brackish water and it is absent only from 
<collectingCountry box="[311,440,698,724]" name="Antarctica" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,763,931]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The rank elevation of the suborder 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" authorityYear="2002" box="[597,732,763,789]" class="Demospongiae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Spongillida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="subOrder" subOrder="Spongillina">Spongillina</taxonomicName>
to the order 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" authorityYear="2002" box="[880,1015,763,789]" class="Demospongiae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Spongillida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Spongillida</taxonomicName>
was proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cardenas" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Cardenas" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="79 - 209" refId="ref6727" refString="Cardenas P., Perez T. &amp; Boury-Esnault N. 2012. Sponge systematics facing new challenges. Advances in Marine Biology 61: 79 - 209. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / b 978 - 0 - 12 - 387787 - 1.00010 - 6" type="journal article" year="2012">
Cárdenas 
<emphasis box="[1340,1391,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al</emphasis>
. (2012)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Morrow &amp; Cardenas" box="[325,658,798,825]" firstAuthor="Morrow" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref9031" refString="Morrow C. &amp; Cardenas P. 2015. Proposal for a revised classification of the Demospongiae (Porifera). Frontiers in Zoology 12: 7 (27 pages). http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1186 / s 12983 - 015 - 0099 - 8" type="book" year="2015">Morrow &amp; Cárdenas (2015)</bibRefCitation>
, confirming the monophyly of freshwater sponges on the basis of both morphological (
<bibRefCitation author="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" box="[464,779,834,860]" firstAuthor="Manconi" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="921 - 1019" refId="ref8380" refString="Manconi R. &amp; Pronzato R. 2002. Spongillina n. subord. Lubomirskiidae, Malawispongiidae n. fam., Metaniidae, Metschnikowiidae, Palaeospongillidae, Potamolepidae, Spongillidae. In: Hooper J. N. A. &amp; van Soest R. W. M. (eds) Systema Porifera. A guide to the classification of sponges, Vol. 1: 921 - 1019. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publisher, New York. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 97" type="journal article" year="2002">Manconi &amp; Pronzato 2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" box="[790,849,834,860]" firstAuthor="Manconi" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="341 - 366" refId="ref8603" refString="Manconi R. &amp; Pronzato R. 2011. Suborder Spongillina (freshwater sponges). In: Pansini M., Manconi R. &amp; Pronzato R. (eds) Porifera I. Calcarea, Demospongiae (partim), Hexactinellida, Homoscleromorpha. Fauna d'Italia, vol. 46: 341 - 366. Calderini, Bologna." type="journal article" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
) and molecular analyses (
<bibRefCitation author="Itskovich" box="[1150,1393,834,860]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Itskovich" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="275 - 280" refId="ref7791" refString="Itskovich V. B., Belikov S. I., Efremova S. M. &amp; Masuda Y. 1999. Phylogenetic relationships between Lubomirskiidae, Spongillidae and some marine sponges according partial sequences of 18 S rDNA. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum 44: 275 - 280. Available from http: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 40271025 [accessed 12 Sep. 2016]" type="journal article" year="1999">
Itskovich 
<emphasis box="[1268,1319,834,860]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al</emphasis>
. 1999
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Itskovich V. &amp; Belikov S. &amp; Efremova S. &amp; Masuda Y. &amp; Perez T. &amp; Alivon E. &amp; Borchiellini C. &amp; Esnault N." box="[189,251,869,895]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="383 - 391" refId="ref7862" refString="Itskovich V., Belikov S., Efremova S., Masuda Y., Perez T., Alivon E., Borchiellini C. &amp; Boury- Esnault N. 2007. Phylogenetic relationships between freshwater and marine Haplosclerida (Porifera, Demospongiae) based on the full length 18 S rRNA and partial COXI gene sequences. In: Custodio M. R., Lobo-Hajdu G., Hajdu E. &amp; Muricy G. (eds) Porifera Research: Biodiversity, Innovation and Sustainability. Serie Livros: 383 - 391. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro." type="book chapter" year="2007">2007</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Itskovich V. &amp; Gontcharov A. &amp; Masuda Y. &amp; Nohno T. &amp; Belikov S. &amp; Efremova S. &amp; Meixner M. &amp; Janussen D." box="[264,326,869,895]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="608 - 620" refId="ref7967" refString="Itskovich V., Gontcharov A., Masuda Y., Nohno T., Belikov S., Efremova S., Meixner M. &amp; Janussen D. 2008. Ribosomal ITS sequences allow resolution of freshwater sponge phylogeny with alignments guided by secondary structure prediction. Journal of Molecular Evolution 67: 608 - 620. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00239 - 008 - 9158 - 5" type="journal article" year="2008">2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Addis &amp; Peterson" box="[338,621,869,896]" firstAuthor="Addis" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="549 - 557" refId="ref6424" refString="Addis J. S. &amp; Peterson K. J. 2005. Phylogenetic relationships of freshwater sponges (Porifera, Spongillina) inferred from analyses of 18 S rDNA, COI mtDNA, and ITS 2 rDNA sequences. Zoologica Scripta 34: 549 - 557. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1463 - 6409.2005.00211. x" type="journal article" year="2005">Addis &amp; Peterson 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Meixner" box="[635,875,869,896]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Meixner" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="875 - 886" refId="ref8881" refString="Meixner M. J., Luter C., Eckert C., Itskovich V., Janussen D., von Rintelen T., Bohne A. V., Meixner J. M. &amp; Hess W. R. 2007. Phylogenetic analysis of freshwater sponges provide evidence for endemism and radiation in ancient lakes. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 45: 875 - 886. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2007.09.007" type="journal article" year="2007">
Meixner 
<emphasis box="[744,797,869,895]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Redmond" box="[889,1143,869,896]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Redmond" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="344 - 352" refId="ref9439" refString="Redmond N. E., van Soest R. W. M., Kelly M., Raleigh J., Travers S. A. A. &amp; McCormack G. P. 2007. Reassessment of the classification of the Order Haplosclerida (Class Demospongiae, Phylum Porifera) using 18 S rRNA gene sequence data. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 43: 344 - 352. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.10.021" type="journal article" year="2007">
Redmond 
<emphasis box="[1012,1065,869,895]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Morrow" box="[1157,1394,869,896]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Morrow" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="174 - 190" refId="ref9082" refString="Morrow C. C., Picton B. M., Erpenbeck D., Boury-Esnault N., Maggs C. &amp; Allock L. 2012. Congruence between nuclear and mitochondrial genes in Demospongiae: A new hypothesis for relationships within the G 4 clade (Porifera: Demospongiae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 62: 174 - 190. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2011.09.016" type="journal article" year="2012">
Morrow 
<emphasis box="[1262,1315,869,895]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Morrow &amp; Cardenas" box="[189,503,904,931]" firstAuthor="Morrow" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref9031" refString="Morrow C. &amp; Cardenas P. 2015. Proposal for a revised classification of the Demospongiae (Porifera). Frontiers in Zoology 12: 7 (27 pages). http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1186 / s 12983 - 015 - 0099 - 8" type="book" year="2015">Morrow &amp; Cárdenas 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,970,1172]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Summarizing, from a morphological point of view, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manconi &amp; Pronzato" authorityYear="2002" box="[858,993,970,996]" class="Demospongiae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Spongillida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Spongillida</taxonomicName>
are characterised by a skeletal architecture of monaxonid spicules (oxeas, styles, and strongyles) organized in isotropic/anisotropic networks of mono- to multi-spicular fibres, with scanty to abundant spongin. Microscleres are often present. Megascleres present as smooth, tubercled to variably spiny monaxons. The presence of resting bodies named gemmules is a trait shared by most families, genera, and species (ca 89%). Gemmules are a key diagnostic trait at genus and species levels. The closest taxon is the marine order 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1928" box="[1211,1378,1146,1172]" class="Demospongiae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Haplosclerida</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
